$\color{blue}{Figure\ 1}$ plots the training and validation accuracy of the model across training steps. The test accuracy reaches 87.1%9, comparable to the accuracy of other photo sentiment classification models in the literature. For example, $\color{blue}{Campos\ et\ al.\ (2017)}$ compared various modifications of CNN models trained on DeepSent and reported test set accuracy values ranging from 78.3% to 83.0%. To further evaluate model performance, the authors also computed recall (86.2%), precision (94.3%), and F1 (90.1%)10.

(Precision measures how accurately the model identifies positive photos among all photos predicted as positive (an important metric when the cost of false positives is high). Recall measures how accurately the model identifies positive photos from all actual positive photos in the sample (an important metric when the cost of false negatives is high). F1 is the harmonic mean of precision and recall.)






